[[File:Seattle - Moore Theatre - poles1.jpg|thumb| A selection of stage braces]]

In theater, a '''brace''' is a sliding  piece of [[wood]] or [[metal]] with a 'butterfly' winged nut to make it longer or shorter to fit the flat used to stabilize a flat [[set (theater)|set]] piece such as a [[flats (theatre)|flat]]. The nut is used, so that it can be changed more quickly than a screw to the floor during a quick change. Usually, a brace is painted black to make it less noticeable to the audience. Braces are often used to form a triangle between two perpendicular items (like a vertical flat and a [[stage (theatre)|stage]]. They can also make a flat piece stronger by forming an X-shape between all four corners. Another way to brace a [[rectangular]] flat is to use special braces, called ''toggles'' which run at regular intervals, [[Parallel (geometry)|parallel]] to the short end of the flat, effectively breaking it into many smaller, stronger rectangles.

