{{Infobox music genre | name = Cine-variety | stylistic_origins = | cultural_origins = Early 20th century, [[United Kingdom]] | instruments = | derivatives = | subgenres = | fusiongenres = {{unbulleted list|[[Film|Cinema]]|[[Variety show|Variety]]}} | bgcolor = #E9D66B | color = #826644 | image = File:Trocadero - Advert for the opening.jpg | caption = Advert for the Trocadero on [[New Kent Road]], London, which opened in December 1930. It was described as ‘Europe’s largest cine-variety theatre’ }}
'''Cine-variety''' is a form of entertainment with a mix of [[Music hall|variety acts]] performing in between the showing of [[film]]s all for the price of one admission fee.<ref name="Ireland"/> It was popular in the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Ireland]] between 1900 and the 1930s.<ref name="Ireland">{{cite web|url=https://www.historyireland.com/20th-century-contemporary-history/the-theatre-royal-a-palace-of-cine-variety/|publisher= History Publications Ltd|title=The Theatre Royal— a palace of cine-variety| accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> Cine-variety was used to keep stage comedians in work during the early days of [[silent film]]s and [[Sound film|talking films]].<ref name="dictionary">{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionarycentral.com/definition/cine-variety.html|publisher=Dictionary Central|title=Cine-Variety| accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>
==History==
From 1900 many of the first purpose-built cinemas had pianos, organs, and occasionally a small orchestra to accompany films.<ref name="Memories">{{cite web|url=https://mikelangcinevariety.wordpress.com/cine-variety-memories-of-a-forgotten-era/|publisher=Mike Lang |title=Cine-Variety: Memories of a Forgotten Era | accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> They also employed live acts on stage, along with the silent film.<ref name="Memories"/> The types of acts that would be employed included [[comedy routine]]s, [[Acrobatics|acrobat]]s, [[singers]], [[Entertainment|entertainers]] and [[Magic (illusion)|magicians]].<ref name="Ireland 2">{{cite web|url=http://d1010382.cp.irishdomains.com/122/_3.2%20Cine-Variety%202008-05.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=[[Film Ireland]]|title=The History of Irish Cinemas &ndash; Part 2: Cine-Variety in Dublin| accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref> By the 1930s the cinema showing would usually include a [[feature film]], a [[B movie]], a [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]] for the following week’s show, a [[newsreel]], a [[cartoon]] plus a full live stage show.<ref name="Memories"/> Those in the show were often stars of film, radio, or [[Variety show|variety theatre]].<ref name="Memories"/> Most of the cinema chains in the UK and Ireland employed stars for their cine-variety as part of the show.<ref name="Memories"/> This included stars such as [[Cicely Courtneidge]], [[Teddy Brown]] and [[Tommy Handley]] from the film ''[[Elstree Calling]]'' and [[Clapham and Dwyer]], [[Claude Dampier]], [[Ronald Frankau]] and [[Edward Stanelli|Stanelli]] from the film ''[[Radio Parade of 1935]]''.<ref name="Memories"/><ref name="BFI">{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6b3d1c35|publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |title=Radio Parade of 1935 (1935)| accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> Although cine-variety's heyday was in the 1930s, it continued through the 1950s with the shows at [[Empire, Leicester Square|The Empire]], [[Leicester Square]], [[London]].<ref name="Empire">{{cite web|url=http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/EmpireLeicesterSquare/CVProg.htm |publisher=www.arthurlloyd.co.uk |title=A Cine-Variety Programme for the Empire Theatre, Leicester Square, March 1950| accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> The Theatre Royal in Winchester describes itself as "the only surviving cine-variety theatre in the country",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatreroyalwinchester.co.uk/about-us/|publisher=Theatre Royal Winchester |title=About us| accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> it opened as a cine-variety theatre in 1914.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatreroyalwinchester.co.uk/about-us/history/|publisher=Theatre Royal Winchester |title=History| accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Cinema of Ireland]] *[[Cinema of the United Kingdom]] *[[Irish theatre|Theatre of Ireland]] *[[Theatre of the United Kingdom]]
