{{multiple issues| {{Notability|Bio|date=June 2017}} {{BLP sources|date=June 2017}} {{third-party|date=June 2017}} }} {{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}} {{Infobox writer | name = Jake Adelstein | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = Joshua Lawrence Adelstein | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|03|28}} | birth_place = [[Columbia, Missouri]] | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Journalist, [[private investigator|investigator]], writer, researcher, [[risk analysis|risk analyst]], editor, [[Blogger (person)|blogger]] | language = | nationality = American | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = [[True crime|True crime]], non-fiction, journalism | subject = | movement = | notableworks = ''[[Tokyo Vice|Tokyo Vice: An American Reporter on the Police Beat in Japan]]'' | spouse = | partner = | children = 2 | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = | module = | website = [http://www.japansubculture.com/ www.japansubculture.com] | portaldisp = }}
'''Jake Adelstein''' (born March 28, 1969) is a [[United States|Jewish-American]]<ref>Jake Adelstein, [https://twitter.com/jakeadelstein/status/614343052086259713 "Yakuza, strippers, drugs, an undercover Japanese-Jew FBI special agent? Pulp non-fiction."], ''[[Twitter]]'', June 26, 2015.</ref> journalist, [[crime writer]], and blogger who has spent most of his career in Japan. He is the author of ''[[Tokyo Vice|Tokyo Vice: An American Reporter on the Police Beat in Japan.]]''
==Career== Adelstein grew up in [[Missouri]] and moved to [[Japan]] at age 19 to study Japanese literature at [[Sophia University]].<ref name=Hessler>Hessler, Peter. "All Due Respect" [http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2012/01/09/120109fa_fact_hessler Profile], ''[[The New Yorker]]'', January 9, 2012.</ref> In 1993, Adelstein became the first non-Japanese staff writer at the ''[[Yomiuri Shinbun]]'' newspaper, where he worked for 12 years.<ref name="ABC">Mark Willacy, [http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/10/20/2718773.htm "Exposing Japan's Insidious Underbelly"], [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]], October 20, 2009; accessed November 20, 2010.</ref>
After leaving the ''Yomiuri'', Adelstein published an exposé of how an alleged crime boss, [[Tadamasa Goto]], made a deal with the FBI to gain entry to the United States for a liver transplant at the [[University of California Los Angeles]] (UCLA). In 2009, Adelstein published a memoir about his career as a reporter in Japan, ''[[Tokyo Vice]]'', in which he accused Goto of threatening to kill him over the story. <ref name="adelstein post">Jake Adelstein, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/05/09/AR2008050902544.html "This Mob Is Big in Japan"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', May 11, 2008, Accessed November 20, 2010</ref>
Adelstein was subsequently a reporter for a [[United States Department of State]] investigation into [[human trafficking]] in Japan, and now writes for the ''[[Daily Beast]]'', ''[[Vice News]]'', ''[[The Japan Times]]'' and other publications. He is a board member and advisor to the [[Lighthouse: Center for Human Trafficking Victims]] (formerly Polaris Project Japan).
On April 19, 2011, Adelstein filed a lawsuit against [[National Geographic Television]], which had hired him to help make a documentary about the yakuza, citing ethical problems with their behavior in Japan.<ref>{{cite news| author = Eriq Gardner| title = NatGeo Delays Japanese Mafia Show at Center of Lawsuit (Updated)| quote =| newspaper =[[The Hollywood Reporter]]| date = May 10, 2011 | url =http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/natgeo-delays-japanese-mafia-show-187052| accessdate =August 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Superior>Superior Court of the District of Columbia. (http://www.courthousenews.com/2011/05/06/Yakuza.pdf), April 19, 2011.</ref> Adelstein withdrew the lawsuit a month later, after reaching a settlement.<ref>Superior Court of the District of Columbia. (http://www.courthousenews.com/2011/05/06/Notice%20of%20Dismissal%20with%20Prejudice.pdf), May 4, 2011.</ref>
