{{Infobox language |name=Yapese |states=[[Federated States of Micronesia]] |region=Island of [[Yap]] |speakers=5,130 |date=2005 |ref={{r|Ethnologue}} |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] |fam4=[[Admiralty Islands languages|Admiralty Islands]]? |dia1=[[Nguluwan language|Nguluwan]] |script= [[Latin script]] |iso2=yap |iso3=yap |glotto=yape1250 |glottorefname=Yapesic }}
'''Yapese''' is a language spoken by the people on the [[island]] of [[Yap]] ([[Federated States of Micronesia]]). It belongs to the [[Austronesian languages]], more specifically to the [[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] branch of that family. It has been difficult to classify it further, but Yapese may prove to be one of the [[Admiralty Islands languages]].{{r|Lynchetal2002}}
==Orthography== [[File:Oceanic languages.svg|thumb|left|The branches of the [[Oceanic languages]]. Orange is the Admiralties languages and Yapese, yellow-orange is [[St Matthias languages|St. Matthias]], green is [[Western Oceanic languages|Western Oceanic]], violet is [[Temotu languages|Temotu]], and the rest are [[Central-Eastern Oceanic languages|Central-Eastern]]: dark red [[Southeast Solomonic languages|Southeast Solomons]], blue [[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic]], pink [[Micronesian languages|Micronesian]], and ocher [[Central Pacific languages|Central Pacific linkage]].]]
Written Yapese uses [[Latin script]]. In Yapese spelling as practised until the 1970s, the glottal stop was not written with an explicit character. A word-final glottal stop was represented by doubling the final vowel letter. [[Glottalization]] of consonants was represented with an apostrophe. In the 1970s an orthography was created which uses double vowel letters to represent long vowels; and because of the ambiguity that would occur if the glottal stop was not written, the glottal stop was written with the letter ''q''. This new orthography using the letter ''q'' is not in universal use, but many works and maps about Yap represent place names using the orthography and contain amounts of the letter ''q'' that are likely to be puzzling to persons not familiar with the language and the new orthography.
==Phonology==
Apart from a couple grammatical forms which are V, syllables are CV or CVC.
===Consonants===
Yapese is one of the relatively few languages in the world with [[ejective consonant|ejective]] [[fricative]]s.<ref>{{SOWL|178}}</ref> The Yapese ejective consonants are {{IPA|/pʼ tʼ kʼ θʼ/}}. There are also glottalised nasals {{IPA|/mˀ nˀ ŋˀ/}} and approximants {{IPA|/jˀ wˀ lˀ/}}.{{r|Jensen1977|p=30, 34-35}}
In the table below, each [[phoneme]] is listed to the left of the [[grapheme]] that represents it in Yapese orthography.
{| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" ! colspan="2" | ! [[Labial consonant|Labial]] ! [[Dental consonant|Dental]] ! [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ! [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! [[Velar consonant|Velar]] ! [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- ! rowspan="2" | [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] ! <small>plain</small> | {{IPA link|m}} ''m'' | | {{IPA link|n}} ''n'' | | {{IPA link|ŋ}} ''ng'' | |- ! <small>[[Glottalization|glottalized]]</small> | mˀ ''m''' | | nˀ ''n''' | | ŋˀ ''ng''' | |- ! rowspan="2" | [[Stop consonant|Plosive]] ! <small>plain</small> | {{IPA link|p}} ''p'' | | {{IPA link|t}} ''t'' | | {{IPA link|k}} ''k'' | {{IPA link|ʔ}} ''q''/''[']'' |- ! <small>[[Ejective consonant|ejective]]</small> | {{IPA link|pʼ}} ''p''' | | {{IPA link|tʼ}} ''t''' | | {{IPA link|kʼ}} ''k''' | |- ! rowspan=3 | [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] ! <small>[[voicelessness|voiceless]]</small> | {{IPA link|f}} ''f'' | {{IPA link|θ}} ''th'' | {{IPA link|s}} ''s'' | {{IPA link|ʃ}} ''ch'' | {{IPA link|x}} ''g'' | ({{IPA link|h}}) ''h'' |- ! <small>[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small> | {{IPA link|β}} ''b'' | {{IPA link|ð}} ''d'' | | | | |- ! <small>[[ejective consonant|ejective]]</small> | | {{IPA link|θʼ}} ''th''' | | | | |- ! rowspan="2" | [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] ! <small>plain</small> | | | {{IPA link|l}} ''l'' | {{IPA link|j}} ''y''/''j'' | {{IPA link|w}} ''w'' | |- ! <small>glottalized</small> | | | lˀ ''l''' | jˀ ''y''' | wˀ ''w''' | |- ! rowspan=3 | [[Trill consonant|Trill]] ! <small>plain</small> | | | {{IPA link|r}} ''r'' | | | |}
/h/ <h> and /j/ <j> only occur in English and Japanese loans (/j/ <y> does occur in native words, however).
